SIMPLE: lode
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Lode
<hw>Lode</hw> <pr>(l⟦omac⟧d)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS.
<ets>l⟦amac⟧d</ets> way, journey, fr. <ets>l⟦imac⟧⟦edh⟧an</ets> to go.
See <er>Lead</er> to guide, and cf. <er>Load</er> a burden.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>A water course or way; a reach of water.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Down that long, dark <qex>lode</qex> . . . he and his brother
skated home in triumph.</q> <rj><qau>C. Kingsley.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Mining)</fld> <def>A body of ore visibly separated
from adjacent rock.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <specif>Especially:</specif> <fld>(Mining)</fld> <def>Any
regular vein or course of valuable mineral, whether metallic or
not.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <specif>Hence:</specif> <def>A concentrated supply or
source of something valuable.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>mother lode</b></col> <cd>a large concentrated source of
mineral or other valuable thing, from which lesser sources have been
derived; -- often used figuratively. The term may have been originally
applied to real or imagined large deposits of gold from which smaller
granules were washed downstream, there constituting a diluted source of
gold, and hinting at the richer source from which they were derived;
<as>as, to hit the <ex>mother lode</ex></as>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Lodemanage</ent>⟦br⟧
